The problem of agency in the acquisition of ownership and possession, upon which there is a good deal in this Title, may be stated thus ι·- Will delivery of possession, or conveyance of ownership, to -B, acting as agent for A, make A possessor or owner without more, oris it necessary that there shall be a second conveyance from B to A? This question the old law answered in the negative: it tolerated only one necessary exception. Some persons, viz. slaves, filiifamilias, and those in manu or mancipio, could not hold property owing to their subjection to a superior: if ownership or possession (as to the latter there was a doubt in respect of those in manu or mancipio, Gaius ii. 90) was transferred to them, the conveyance‚ unless it was to be nugatory, must enure solely to the benefit of the superior : they served solely as conduitpipes through whom rights passed instantaneously to the latter, Gaius ii. 86-88. Other gradual modifications of the strict old rule are noticed in the text and following notes.
